We went to Botiwalla, the Indian spot tucked inside Optimist Hall. What about the food, you ask? Spectacular. A bold, balanced blend of spice and flavor that actually tastes like something. I took one bite of the lamb slider and, like that scene in Ratatouille, I was gone—back to my teenage years in India, back to the street stalls and smoky grills and the kind of food that stays with you.

The manager was just as impressive. Checked in after our first few bites—not in a scripted way, but genuinely. Asked if anything needed correcting, brought over extra plates so we could share. Thoughtful, present, and clearly proud of the place.

Don’t wait. Run. This is the kind of food that makes you feel something.

Given the parking experience, I can’t give a high rating—as I posted in a review on the “Optimist Hall parking” Google page:

“Agree w/everyone, turns into $18 for over 3 hours very quickly, I’m sending this to the Charlotte Observer and WFAE for them to look into it. Optimus Hall is no doubt making hand over fist w/all their customers, they need to fix the parking situation.”

I did appreciate a lot of the inside of Optimist Hall, but it’s basically a spot for people w/disposable income and/or has an extortionist vibe for those without extra money for high parking and quick fines if they don’t figure out some fair parking situation (not to mention just about everything but the food is majorly over-priced). The parking signs at least need to change from something about the first part being free and the next couple hours being $5 or so (which they do have now), to add that it goes up to $18 (!) if you’re there over 3 hours.

The predatory parking lot lures people in with 2 hours free parking but then they get a ticket for $50. Hundreds of reviewers say the same. Unfortunately they are on the parking lot location, not here where they would belong. The operator and city purposefully trick the guests here and basically scam them. The restaurants here need to do something to stop this money grab scam

Optimist Hall in Charlotte is an absolute gem! The food options are incredibly diverse — whether you’re craving tacos, Ethiopian, sushi, burgers, or gourmet coffee, there’s something for every palate. It’s like a global food tour all under one roof. The quality is top-notch, and the variety makes it easy to come back again and again without getting bored.

The vibe is lively yet laid-back, with a perfect mix of industrial-chic design and cozy gathering spots. It’s a great place for everything from a solo lunch to a date night or group hangout. The open layout, natural light, and communal seating give it a welcoming energy, while still letting each food stall shine with its own unique character.

The setup is smart and efficient — plenty of seating inside and out, easy-to-navigate food stalls, and lots of little nooks to settle in and enjoy your meal. Whether you’re there to eat, work remotely, or just hang out, Optimist Hall hits the mark. Highly recommend checking it out!

The historical architecture and industrial style are right up my alley - it’s a beautiful building with so much character. We were especially thrilled to finally catch The Dumpling Lady without chasing down a food truck.
That said, the charm faded quickly once the crowd rolled in. It felt like we were instantly shouldered out by people more focused on getting the perfect photo for social media than enjoying the atmosphere or food. While I still love the stationery store tucked inside and will definitely stop by again for that, the overall vibe just isn’t for us anymore. We went to Botiwalla, the Indian spot tucked inside Optimist Hall. What about the food, you ask? Spectacular. A bold, balanced blend of spice and flavor that actually tastes like something. I took one bite of the lamb slider and, like that scene in Ratatouille, I was gone—back to my teenage years in India, back to the street stalls and smoky grills and the kind of food that stays with you.

The manager was just as impressive. Checked in after our first few bites—not in a scripted way, but genuinely. Asked if anything needed correcting, brought over extra plates so we could share. Thoughtful, present, and clearly proud of the place.

Don’t wait. Run. This is the kind of food that makes you feel something.

Given the parking experience, I can’t give a high rating—as I posted in a review on the “Optimist Hall parking” Google page:

“Agree w/everyone, turns into $18 for over 3 hours very quickly, I’m sending this to the Charlotte Observer and WFAE for them to look into it. Optimus Hall is no doubt making hand over fist w/all their customers, they need to fix the parking situation.”

I did appreciate a lot of the inside of Optimist Hall, but it’s basically a spot for people w/disposable income and/or has an extortionist vibe for those without extra money for high parking and quick fines if they don’t figure out some fair parking situation (not to mention just about everything but the food is majorly over-priced). The parking signs at least need to change from something about the first part being free and the next couple hours being $5 or so (which they do have now), to add that it goes up to $18 (!) if you’re there over 3 hours.

The predatory parking lot lures people in with 2 hours free parking but then they get a ticket for $50. Hundreds of reviewers say the same. Unfortunately they are on the parking lot location, not here where they would belong. The operator and city purposefully trick the guests here and basically scam them. The restaurants here need to do something to stop this money grab scam

Optimist Hall in Charlotte is an absolute gem! The food options are incredibly diverse — whether you’re craving tacos, Ethiopian, sushi, burgers, or gourmet coffee, there’s something for every palate. It’s like a global food tour all under one roof. The quality is top-notch, and the variety makes it easy to come back again and again without getting bored.

The vibe is lively yet laid-back, with a perfect mix of industrial-chic design and cozy gathering spots. It’s a great place for everything from a solo lunch to a date night or group hangout. The open layout, natural light, and communal seating give it a welcoming energy, while still letting each food stall shine with its own unique character.

The setup is smart and efficient — plenty of seating inside and out, easy-to-navigate food stalls, and lots of little nooks to settle in and enjoy your meal. Whether you’re there to eat, work remotely, or just hang out, Optimist Hall hits the mark. Highly recommend checking it out!

There are a lot of live plants everywhere and the smell of all the different cuisines smelled tantalizing. The wood floors are gorgeous. I think it used to be a textile mill of some sort. Lots of little merchants to choose from too.

I really enjoy the noodles the most and always gotta grab some gelato for the road.

My 7 year old and dad were happy with the hot dogs while my vegetarian brother and I loved the Ethiopian food. All the kids got delicious ice cream for dessert. It was a wonderful place to meet up and great ambiance!

reviews_data.review_text: It’s always fun to go to Optimist Hall!  We love the multiple food options and the outdoor seating is fantastic on a nice day!  The mercantile shopping is very enjoyable with something to interest everyone.  There are also play areas for kids and the parking is free for the first 90 minutes, unless you can score a spot at the Duke Energy building next door (weekends only).  The noise level outside is very manageable, but inside isn’t too difficult for conversation.

reviews_data.review_text: Super fantastic place and food!

Hey there! 😊 Honestly, everything in the market is just so perfect. Parking? Absolutely free and right in front of the market itself! You'll instantly feel the vibes once you reach, it's like a giant food court but way more local and upscale. 🥘

They've set up such unique shops, everything from a candy store 🍭 to a place specialized in treats for our furry friends 🐶. The range of food they had was vast, dumplings, ramen, you name it. I ended up dining at Noble Smoke, highly recommend their BBQ. Ordered brisket, mac n cheese, and collards - every bite was a delight. 💯

I couldn't resist some sweet indulgence on my way out and bought myself a tres leches - trust me when I say this, it was sublime! 😋 So many other options still left to explore, can't wait for my next visit! The atmosphere, vibe, food, everything on point. 👌

Hope you can join next time!
